# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balochi-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The **1970s operation in Balochistan**, also known as the **Fourth Balochistan Conflict** was a four-year military conflict in Balochistan, the largest province of Pakistan, between the Pakistan Army and Baloch separatists and tribesmen that lasted from 1973 to 1977.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The conflict began in 1973 shortly after then-Pakistani President Zulfikar Ali Bhutto dismissed the elected provincial government of Balochistan on the pretext that arms had been discovered in the Iraqi Embassy, ostensibly for Baloch rebels.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The ensuing protest against the dismissal of the duly elected government also led to calls for Balochistan's secession, met by Bhutto's ordering the Pakistan Army into the province.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Akbar Khan Bugti served as provincial governor during the early stages of the conflict.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The operation itself was led by General Tikka Khan against an unknown number of militants coordinated by their Baloch sardars, or tribal chiefs, most notably Khair Bakhsh Marri and Ataullah Mengal.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Iran provided military support to the operation.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Fighting was intermittent throughout the conflict, climaxing in 1974 with drawn-out battles.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The Bhutto regime was overthrown by General Zia-ul-Haq on 5 July 1977, and martial law was imposed.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] A general amnesty was declared by military governor Rahimuddin Khan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Military action ended by November 1977, replaced by development and educational policies to conciliate the province.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The 1971 civil war had ended with the defeat of Pakistan at the hands of Bangladesh.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] East Pakistan declared itself to be independent.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] It became a new sovereign state called Bangladesh, to be ruled by Bengali leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Despite Mujib's having won the federal elections of 1970, both Yahya and Bhutto refused to let Mujib form the central government.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The ensuing unrest gradually deteriorated into civil war, and ultimately the secession of Bangladesh after the India-Pakistan War of 1971.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] India also played a large part in the independence of Bangladesh by arming and financing the separatist group Mukti Bahini which rebelled against the Pakistani State after the injustice done to the then East Pakistan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Most importantly, India sent its troops into East Pakistan to aid the Bengali separatists in suppressing the Pakistan army .
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] This greatly influenced Balochistan's leading political party, the National Awami Party (NAP).
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Led by ethnic nationalists and feudal leaders such as Sardar Ataullah Mengal and Khan Wali Khan, the party dominated the province due to the large amount of individual political influence its leaders held.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Emboldened by the secession of Bangladesh, the party demanded greater autonomy from Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who had become the new President of Pakistan following his predecessor Yahya Khan's resignation in December 1971, in return for a consensual agreement on Bhutto's Pakistan Constitution of 1973.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Bhutto, however, refused to negotiate on any terms that might have involved a reduction in his powers, with chief minister Ataullah Mengal in Quetta and Mufti Mahmud in Peshawar.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The already significant civil unrest now turned volatile as tensions between the NAP and Bhutto erupted.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The ethno-separatist rebellion of Balochistan of the 1970s, the most threatening civil disorder to Pakistan since Bangladesh's secession, now began.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Following the alleged discovery of Iraqi arms in Islamabad in February 1973, Bhutto dissolved the Balochistan Provincial Assembly and infuriated Balochistan's political oligarchs.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] In time, the nationalist insurgency, which had been steadily gathering steam, now exploded into action, with widespread civil disobedience and armed uprisings.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Bhutto now sent in the army to maintain order and crush the insurgency.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] This essentially pitted the ethno-separatists against the central government.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] As casualties rose, the insurgency became a full-fledged armed struggle against the Pakistan Army.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The sporadic fighting between the insurgency and the army started in 1973 with the largest confrontation taking place in September 1974 when around 15,000 ethno-separatists fought the Pakistan Army and Air Force.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The army suffered more than 3,000 casualties in the fight while the militants lost some 5,000 fighters as of 1977.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] After four years of fighting, the separatists began running out of ammunition and withdrew by 1977.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Pakistan asserted India was covertly intervening in Balochistan in the same way it had intervened in East Pakistan before the secession of Bangladesh.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] India denied the assertions, replying that it was fearful of further balkanisation of the subcontinent after Bangladesh.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Paliwal further claims that just as Pakistan and India were bitter rivals, so were Iran and Iraq.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] In the pursuit of their respective rivalries, Pakistan and Iran developed closer relations, as did India and Iraq.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Arming Baloch insurgents in Iran and Pakistan was in the interest of both Iraq and India.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The militant group *Pasthun Zalmay* was responsible for a series of bomb blasts and other insurgent activities in Pakistan; it comprised Balochs and Pashtuns and was in direct contact with Kabul as well as with the Indian and Iraqi missions in Afghanistan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] As a consequence, relations between Iran and India deteriorated so much that in 1975, Indian diplomat Ram D.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Sathe sent a secret letter to the Indian ambassador in Tehran in which Sathe predicted that "it will be a few more days before the Iranians will stridently back the Pakistanis (on Kashmir) ...
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Personally I do not think we should be under any illusion about this matter.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] I think Iranians will definitely back the Pakistanis".
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] It was after visiting Iran in 1973 that President Zulfikar Ali Bhutto had dissolved Balochistan's provincial government in the run-up to the operation.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] When the operation was begun, Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, the Shah of Iran and an ally of Bhutto, feared a spread of Baloch ethnic resistance into Iran.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The Imperial Iranian Army began providing Pakistan with military hardware and financial support.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Among Iran's contributions were 30 HueyCobra attack helicopters and $200 million in aid.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] During the conflict, US provided training and military equipment to Pakistan, most notable is the Marine training program to train the Pakistan Army soldiersagainst Baloch separatists.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Moreover many military officers were trained in US as well as many in Pakistan by American forces in this conflict.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] In 1974, an embargo was imposed on Pakistan due to its weapon of mass destruction projects, but due to intensification of the insurgency, it was lifted in 1975 and weapons were sent to Pakistan to deal with the situation.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The Republic of Afghanistan, under the leadership of General Mohammed Daoud Khan, provided covert support to Pashtun and Baloch militants.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Daoud Khan had ordered the construction of military training camps for Pashtun and Baloch militants in Kabul and in Kandahar.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Camps in Kabul were under the supervision and control of the Afghan Republican Guard.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Pashtun and Baloch militants were provided with arms, ammunition, and training in insurgent warfare so that they would fight against Pakistan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Relations between Baloch separatists and Ba'athist Iraq had historical roots and were strong up until the 2003 U.S-led invasion of Iraq.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Following the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971, Iraq had begun to collaborate with the Soviet Union in launching a covert operation to provide military aid to Baloch insurgents operating in Pakistan and Iran.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The aim of this operation was to destabilize the two countries by helping dissident Baloch rebels in their fight against the Iranian and Pakistani states that were close allies with the United States.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The operation remained modestly successful during the early 1970s, but ultimately failed when there was unrest amongst the Baloch nationalist leaders involved in the insurgency due to internal disputes.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The disputes took place when Baloch politicians Ghaus Bakhsh Bizenjo and Ataullah Mengal of the National Awami Party refused to accept the demands of Akbar Bugti to establish himself as the Governor of Pakistani Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] During the Dhofar war, Baloch militants (including BSO) started supporting the Dhofari rebels.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] In a shootout in Balochistan, a Dhofari recruiter from Oman, who came to recruit Balochi mercenaries, was seriously wounded.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] This incident prompted Oman to provide financial support to Pakistan against insurgents.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Moreover, Pakistani troops were also trained in Oman to fight against Baloch separatists.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Due to communist ideology of the insurgents and in an attempt to destabilize Pakistan, a western aligned nation, the Soviet Union had started supporting groups like Balochistan Liberation Front, enabling them to regroup.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] They also provided financial assistance and training to the separatists.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] American defence aid to Pakistan also promoted further Soviet support to the separatists to gain a stronghold in the region in the form of an independent Marxist Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Moreover a Marxist state in the region could break the Green belt isolating Pakistan and breaking direct connection with western aligned states.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Although major fighting had broken down, ideological schisms caused splinter groups to form and steadily gain momentum.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] On 5 July 1977, the Bhutto government was overthrown by General Zia-ul-Haq and martial law was imposed.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] With the civil disobedience in Balochistan remaining widespread, the military brought in Lieutenant General Rahimuddin Khan as governor under martial law.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Rahimuddin declared a general amnesty for belligerents willing to give up arms and oversaw military withdrawal.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Ataullah Mengal, Khair Bakhsh Marri, and Sardars that had been involved in the conflict, were isolated by Rahimuddin from provincial affairs, and left the province for foreign countries.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Marri later said the Baloch independence movement was 'at a virtual standstill', and Marri tribesmen, who had laid down their arms, were granted amnesty.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Akbar Bugti, having sided with Tikka Khan and now being sidelined by Rahimuddin Khan, went into self-imposed seclusion.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] The civil disobedience movements and anti-government protests later died down.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Rahimuddin's tenure also ushered in sustained development.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] He expedited the regulation of Pakistan Petroleum Limited, the exploration company charged with the Sui gas field.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] He consolidated the then-contentious integration of Gwadar into Balochistan, which had earlier been notified as a district in 1977.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] Addressing the province's literacy rate, the lowest in the country for both males and females, he administered the freeing up of resources towards education, created girls' incentive programs, and had several girls' schools built in the Dera Bugti District.
[src:balochi-language/1970s-operation-in-balochistan] As part of his infrastructure schemes, he also forced his way in extending electricity to vast areas with subsoil water.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] The **1973 raid on the Iraqi embassy in Pakistan** was an armed infiltration carried out by Government of Pakistan in February 1973 at the embassy of Ba'athist Iraq in Islamabad.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Following the embassy raid, an abundance of funds and Soviet armaments from Iraq that were meant for Baloch insurgents were seized by Pakistani forces, and the Iraqi ambassador to Pakistan as well as the embassy's staff were immediately expelled from Pakistan and declared *personae non gratae*.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] The event led to a severe deterioration in Iraq–Pakistan relations and contributed to Pakistan's heavy backing of Iran during the latter's eight-year-long war with Iraq.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Relations between Baloch separatists and Ba'athist Iraq had historical roots and were strong up until the 2003 U.S.-led invasion of Iraq.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] The disputes took place when Baloch politicians Ghaus Bakhsh Bizenjo and Ataullah Mengal of the National Awami Party refused to accept the demands of Akbar Bugti to establish himself as the Governor of the Pakistani Province of Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] At midnight on 9 February 1973, Akbar Bugti informed Pakistani authorities about a covert Soviet weapons shipment intended for Baloch insurgents that had been smuggled into the country with Iraqi assistance.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] He reported that the weapons were being kept at the Iraqi embassy in Islamabad.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] On 10 February 1973, Pakistani police and paramilitary forces began to prepare an operation to raid the Iraqi embassy.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] After a few hours of planning, a raid was conducted by the Pakistan Rangers, accompanied by the Islamabad Police to storm the embassy and seize any means of support for the rebels.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] The raid was a success, and Pakistani forces discovered 300 Soviet-made submachine guns with more than 50,000 rounds of ammunition and a large amount of funding intended for Baloch militants.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Following the raid, the Baloch nationalist leader Sher Mohammad Marri paid a formal visit to Baghdad.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Newspapers widely reported that the Soviet arms were intended to be given to Baloch separatists in their fight against Pakistan and Iran to further fuel tensions between the dissident tribes against the two nations.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Media outlets throughout Pakistan predicted that the discovery of these weapons would muster greater support for the government from other ethnic groups in the country.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Supported by Iranian forces, Pakistan launched a large-scale military operation against Baloch rebels shortly after this incident.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] This counter-insurgency operation finally ended in 1977 after the insurgency/rebellion was largely crushed and left disheartened.
[src:balochi-language/1973-raid-on-the-iraqi-embassy-in-pakistan] Despite this setback, Iraq continued to undertake covert activities to empower Baloch nationalists and attempt to destabilize Pakistan and Iran.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] On 25 January 2022, militants stormed an army security post in a remote area of Dasht, Kech District, Balochistan, Pakistan, killing at least ten security personnel and injuring three others.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] The clash lasted for a few hours in which militants also suffered several casualties.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] Additionally, the militants also seized weapons that were present in the security post.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] Locals in the area also confirmed that an attack on the security post took place and that the militants suffered heavy casualties in the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] Pakistani law enforcement agencies say that one militant was killed and several other militants were injured when the militants attacked the security post.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] Three militants responsible for the attack were also arrested by the law enforcement agencies during a search operation in the vicinity of the security post.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] No group has taken responsibility for the attack on security post initially.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] After several days, Gohram Baloch, the spokesperson of the banned Balochistan Liberation Front (BLF) claimed responsibility for the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] The attack on the security post was strongly condemned locally in Pakistan and internationally by Iran, Turkey and United Arab Emirates.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] In response, Pakistan's law enforcement agencies killed six terrorist of Baloch Liberation Front in Injirkan Range near the district's Buleda area on 16 February 2022.
[src:balochi-language/2022-kech-district-attack] The deceased terrorist were part of the group who took part in the raid on security post in Dasht.
[src:balochi-language/2022-panjgur-and-naushki-raids] The **2022 Panjgur and Naushki raids** were a series of attacks on the Pakistani Frontier Corps in Balochistan claimed by the Balochistan Nationalist Army (BNA), a newly formed Balochi separatist group with ties to the Balochistan Liberation Army.
[src:balochi-language/2022-panjgur-and-naushki-raids] On 2 February, the militants attacked both the Frontier Corps base in Nushki and an outpost in Panjgur District, as part of the insurgency in Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The *Jaffar Express*, a Pakistani passenger train travelling from Quetta to Peshawar with at least 380 passengers on board, was hijacked by the Balochistan Liberation Army (BLA) on 11 March 2025.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The attackers detonated explosives in tunnels and on the train tracks before opening fire on the train, halting it in a mountainous region which was difficult for authorities to access.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The organisation issued a 48-hour ultimatum for Baloch political prisoners to be released or they would execute hostages, although they had already released some.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] As a result, Pakistan Railways temporarily suspended its train operations between Balochistan and the provinces of Punjab and Sindh.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] From 11 to 12 March 2025, the Pakistan Armed Forces launched an operation, codenamed **Operation Green Bolan**, to raid the hijacked train multiple times, eventually releasing 354 hostages and killing the 33 BLA insurgents.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistani officials said at least 64 people, including 18 soldiers on leave who were identified among the passengers and killed by the attackers, and 33 attackers, were killed during the incident, while 38 other passengers were injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] In response to the insurgency, the Pakistani political parties unanimously passed a resolution condemning it during a National Assembly session.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Shehbaz Sharif, the Prime Minister of Pakistan, condemned the attack as "cowardly acts", sent condolences to the victims' families and, after the resolution of the crisis, said that the BLA members had been "sent to hell".
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The attack on civilians by BLA was universally condemned by various global figures, who voiced their support towards Pakistan against terrorism.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Afghanistan and India, historically having been accused of assisting the BLA by Pakistan, have both denied claims of involvement in the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Following the attack, Pakistan Railways implemented plans to increase patrol forces in the country's various railway systems and more thoroughly inspect passengers and transport vehicles to prevent similar attacks.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Additionally, both surveillance drones and closed-circuit television cameras were set to be utilised to further monitor train and railway activity upon resumed operations.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Protests in Balochistan, organised by the Baloch Yakjehti Committee (BYC), began on 20 March 2025 in part due to police crackdown on civilians gathering at the Quetta Civil Hospital to identify bodies from the train hijacking.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The province of Balochistan has been involved in insurgencies and conflicts by Baloch separatists against the government of Pakistan since at least 1948.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] This is due to the alleged forced disappearances and violations of the rights of Baloch people by the Pakistan army and extreme poverty as well as under-developed infrastructure in Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Since 2001, armed groups in the region have conducted various violent attacks and campaigns to discourage major development in the region that they believe would benefit other provinces.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Balochistan Liberation Army (BLA) is a Baloch ethnonationalist group founded in 2000.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Members of the organisation stated that their intentions were to achieve regional independence from Pakistan and control over the land's natural resources, primarily its oil and minerals.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The faction had previously launched attacks on civilians and, most often, Pakistani security forces.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] BLA also targets Chinese nationals within the region, as they had been involved in economic infrastructure networking as part of the China–Pakistan Economic Corridor.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] It has officially been banned in Pakistan since 2006.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan had previously accused India and Afghanistan of backing anti-Pakistani militants, which both BLA and the respective countries have denied.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Since then, BLA has launched multiple terrorist attacks that resulted in the deaths of many people; among the most recent attacks in the region prior to the 2025 train hijacking was a November 2024 bombing at Quetta railway station that killed 32.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The *Jaffar Express* passenger train was previously attacked by the BLA near the town of Machh on 7 October 2016 via two explosions that killed six people and injured 19 others.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] At 9 a.m. on 11 March 2025, the *Jaffar Express* train departed Quetta en route to Peshawar, a journey of around 1,600 kilometres (990 mi).
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The train consisted of nine coaches and the locomotive.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Around 450 passengers were reported to have been on board, including military personnel.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Prior to the attack, the BLA insurgents sabotaged the train tracks with 8 improvised explosive devices, so that the train would stop within the mountainous area.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The explosives detonation caused the train's fuel tank to explode, causing a sudden halt and four coaches to derail.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Some 157 kilometres (98 mi) from Quetta and about 21 kilometres (13 mi) west of the city of Sibi, the BLA hijacked the train inside Tunnel No.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] 8, between Pehro Kunri and Mushkaf stations.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The group blew up explosives on the train tracks before opening fire on the train.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Five police officers and two Frontier Corps (FC) personnel escorted the train, and, according to one police officer, "hundreds" of militants surrounded the tracks.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BLA insurgents were equipped with launchers and guns and threatened to kill people if they did not come out of the train.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The defenders fought and engaged with the attackers, giving resistance for over an hour and a half until they were depleted of ammunition which resulted in the defenders eventually being defenceless.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The assistant train driver Saad Qamar used wireless communications to warn a nearby train station about the attack, but it was cut off after the engine was turned off to prevent fire from the leaking diesel cans hit by gunfire.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] As soon as the train stopped, dozens of militants came down from the mountains and boarded the train and separated women and men into groups and checked their identification cards.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to the testimony of a passenger, the assailants did not harm women or elderly people, although another witness stated that the BLA generally rounded hostages up by ethnicity but also executed soldiers or people they did not like on the spot.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Because the hijacking occurred in an isolated mountainous area, the fate of the hostages was not immediately clear.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to Shahid Rind, the Balochistan provincial government spokesman, the surrounding terrain prevented authorities from quickly reaching the area.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan Railways temporarily suspended its train operations between Balochistan and Punjab and Sindh in response to the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] As night fell, most of the attackers withdrew, leaving only 20 to 25 men behind to guard the captives.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] In the darkness, some hostages attempted to flee, but the militants opened fire.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] At dawn, when FC reinforcements arrived, drawing the militants' focus, several people, including a police officer, managed to escape.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The hostages were reported to be mostly law enforcement personnel and non-Baloch civilians.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The militants kept a close watch on the train's security personnel and warned authorities against attempting to rescue the hostages themselves.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Some of the insurgents were equipped with suicide bombs and sat next to the hostages to further prevent an easy rescue by authorities.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BLA spokesman Jeeyand Baloch offered exchanges between the train hostages and jailed militants.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BLA released some civilian hostages such as Balochistan residents, the elderly, women, and children while keeping those who were government workers or military personnel on leave to return to their homes in Punjab for Ramadan.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The same day that the hijacking occurred, BLA issued a 48-hour ultimatum to the Pakistani government in which political prisoners, including Baloch movement affiliates, were to be unconditionally released.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The next day, it threatened to "punish" five hostages for each hour after the ultimatum had expired.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistani officials said they then were yet to communicate with anyone on the train as the area has no internet and mobile network coverage.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistani security forces launched a large-scale counter-operation — named Operation Green Bolan — at the site.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The security forces engaged in the conflict, freeing a majority of the hostages and killing most of the insurgents.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Lasting for over 30 hours, the hostage crisis concluded on 12 March 2025 with 354 total hostages being rescued according to Pakistan's military.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistani officials accused the BLA of using women and children as human shields, which the insurgent group denied.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The rescue was performed mainly by Zarrar Company, an elite unit of the Army’s Special Services Group (SSG).
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to Junior Interior Minister Talal Chaudhry, the Pakistan military sent in hundreds of troops and also deployed the airforce and special forces.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The special forces first killed the suicide bombers and then troops went from carriage to carriage to kill the rest of the militants.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif and his ministers visited Balochistan in response to review the situation and express solidarity with its victims.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to a witness, he and other hostages did not have any food and had to drink water from the train's restroom; the Pakistani army provided the rescued hostages food and water.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Officials confirmed that all 33 militants were killed.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Among the victims were at least three minors.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Officials said they fear the death toll could rise due to the significant number of injuries.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Initially it was reported that the train driver, Amjad Yasin, was killed, but he was later confirmed to have only been injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He was shot in the back when militants opened fire on the train.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Yasin was reported to have been a train driver for 24 years and previously survived a train explosion incident from about 8 years ago.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistani human rights activist Mama Qadeer claimed that over 200 security personnel were killed during the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] At least 17 passengers and three security personnel were injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] A later report suggested that a total of 37 hostages were injured in the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Following the hijack, Pakistan Railways increased security patrols in all railway stations across the country, restricted passenger access to trains through strict examinations, and subjected transport vehicles to more rigorous inspections.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] It further recognised the understaffed railway police force and implemented a plan to hire more personnel in subsequent months.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Railway Minister Hanif Abbasi pledged to give compensations of 5.2 million Pakistani rupees for each family of individuals who were killed in the attack and guaranteed government jobs for their children.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The train suffered severe damage during the attack and an explosion caused damage to both of the train's engines and five coaches.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan Railways Deputy Chief Engineer Rasheed Imtiaz said on the 15 March that it would take them around 12 hours to restore the track.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan Railways engineers worked to repair the train tracks, while the passenger coaches and locomotive have been sent to Lahore for repairment.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] One senior railway official revealed that three of the nine coaches were derailed by the explosive blasts while the rest were riddled with bullets.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to another, 600 m (2,000 ft) of rails were damaged by the explosions and derailment.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] On 27 March, the *Jaffar Express* resumed operations and was decorated with the Pakistan national flag, balloons, and crêpe paper to celebrate its return to service.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] According to Amir Muqam, the minister managing the Ministry of Kashmir Affairs and Gilgit-Baltistan, 300 passengers were on board for the first trip.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He also said that the train's resumed operations were meant to display that Pakistan was not intimidated.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Officials later confirmed that the Jaffar Express left with more than 400 people on board with heavy security arrangements made to protect them and staff members.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BLA claimed responsibility for the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] BLA spokesperson Jeeyand Baloch released a statement claiming that more than 50 personnel from law enforcement agencies, including Pakistan Army soldiers who were reportedly going home on leave, were killed along with 214 hostages.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Four suspected facilitators behind the attack were confirmed to have been arrested by the Counter Terrorism Department.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] On 14 March 2025, Lieutenant General Ahmed Sharif Chaudhry claimed that the BLA insurgents were aided by "handlers in Afghanistan" and a mastermind in India.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He said that the BLA militants were facilitated under the directions of cooperators and a lead mastermind, who contacted them from Afghanistan via a satellite phone but showed no proofs against the claims mentioned.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Pakistan reiterated his claim that facilitators from Afghanistan helped to organise the attack and also blamed India for being behind the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Chief Minister of Balochistan Sarfraz Bugti said that he had "solid evidence" regarding India's involvement but chose not to share any specifics.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Railway Minister Hanif Abbasi accused India of attempting to destabilise Pakistan, especially due to the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan's leaders voiced strong opposition towards the hijack of the *Jaffar Express*, with President Asif Ali Zardari praising his country's security forces for rescuing the passengers from the BLA.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif expressed hope that the security forces could eliminate the "coward terrorists", whom he considered enemies of Balochistan's progress.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] In a post on X, Sharif said that he spoke to Balochistan Chief Minister Sarfraz Bugti regarding the hijacking, and condemned the incident as "cowardly acts" that did not subvert his nation's goals for "resolve for peace" in a speech the day after the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He also expressed condolences for the "families of the martyrs", wished survivors swift recoveries, and stated that the insurgents "have been sent to hell".
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Multiple other prominent Pakistani politicians, namely Interior Minister Mohsin Naqvi, Sindh Home Minister Zia Ul Hassan Lanjar, Senate Chairman Yusuf Raza Gilani, and the National Assembly Speaker Sardar Ayaz Sadiq, also condemned the attack directly.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Railway Minister Hanif Abbasi argued that the BLA's train attack was coordinated and part of a foreign conspiracy.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He confirmed the rescue of all passengers from the attack but declined to give further details about the process other than that a rescue train had arrived to assist them.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He later praised Pakistan's armed forces for their rapid rescue operation, in particular its commandos for preventing suicide bombers from detonating their explosives.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan Army lieutenant general Ahmed Sharif Chaudhry condemned harm towards civilians and stated that whoever was responsible for the incident will be hunted down and brought to justice.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] He added that the attack "changes the rules of the game".
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Punjab governor Sardar Saleem Haider Khan also condemned the attack, considering the insurgents to be inhuman for targeting civilians and wishing for the speedy recovery of injured victims.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) party leader Asad Qaiser voiced concern over the attack but also claimed that Balochistan's flawed government policies allowed for it to occur.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan People's Party leader and digital media head Umar Rehman Malik strongly condemned the attack emphasising that such cowardly acts will never break Pakistan's spirit or weaken the nation's unwavering resolve against terrorism.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Malik gave his condolences to the victims and their families and commended the efforts and swift response of the security forces.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] In a statement, Malik said "Our prayers are with the victims and their families, and we hope for the safe rescue of all hostages and the swift recovery of the injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The perpetrators of this heinous attack must be brought to justice.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Pakistan will never bow to terror, Inshallah." The party's chairman Bilawal Bhutto Zardari called for revisiting the National Action Plan to better counter terrorism, criticising the prime minister for not yet having done so.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] On X, the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan said it was "gravely concerned" by the attack and advocated for "urgent rights-based, pro-people consensus on the issues faced by citizens in Balochistan and to find a peaceful, political solution".
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Following the conflict, the BLA rejected the Pakistani military's claim to the hijack conflict having ended, arguing that battles were still continuing and that Pakistani forces were suffering heavy casualties; they claimed that they executed 214 hostages but did not provide evidence for such.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] On 13 March 2025, governmental parties threw accusations at each other during a National Assembly conference.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Khawaja Asif, the Minister of Defence and a member of the Pakistan Muslim League (N) party, disapproved of PTI for discrediting the military's operation against the BLA.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Asad Qaiser of PTI responded by blaming the conflict on the failures of intelligence agencies and Sharif's regime.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The involved parties unanimously passed a resolution condemning the hijacking incident of the *Jaffar Express* and commending the Pakistani military and law enforcement agencies for their actions.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Multiple Pakistani universities held rallies to condemn the train attack directly, namely Karachi University, Shaheed Mohtarma Benazir Bhutto Medical University, University of Sindh, Sindh Madressatul Islam University, and Sukkur IBA University.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] In the immediate aftermath of the hijacking, Pakistani users on social media spread conspiracy theories alleging that India was involved, with several of them blaming the Research and Analysis Wing.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Indian users made social media posts responding to the incident by taunting Pakistan.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Punjab Information Minister Azma Bukhari accused PTI of running an "anti-state campaign" that created "political divides".
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Beginning on 20 March 2025, families had attempted to gather around the Quetta Civil Hospital, hoping to identify the 23 bodies from the train hijack that were brought there.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Police forces began attacking the gatherers using batons to try to disperse them, injuring several women in the process.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Further outrage from the civilians were sparked upon reports that 13 of the bodies were quickly buried at the Kasi graveyard by police forces, some of whom wanted to identify them.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The public protests led to authorities allowing some families in the hospital and returning 5 bodies to their relatives.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The protests continued to the 21 March when police forces were overwhelmed by protesters, some of whom broke into the civil hospital and stole the bodies; the hospital officials claimed that they were linked to the Baloch Yakjehti Committee (BYC), which was confirmed true by its activists.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Authorities stated that the bodies at the civil hospital's morgue were of unidentified terrorists.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Authorities confirmed that subsequent calls for protests were fuelled by the conflict between protesters and police in response to the militants' bodies.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] On 22 March, the Quetta protests were cracked down upon by police.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Baloch Yakjehti Committee accused police forces of using excessive force against the protesters by firing at them, killing three of them and injuring dozens of others, including seven who were critically injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Balochistan's government spokesman Shahid Rind claimed that the protesters provoked police using stone-throwing and other methods of violence.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] BYC chief and Baloch human rights activist Mahrang Baloch led the protests and vowed a sit-in at Sariab Road.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Protesters proceeded to launch a sit-in at Sariab Road near the University of Balochistan, where police used tear gas, water cannons, and blank rounds to disperse them.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Bolan Medical College Hospital and Quetta Civil Hospital confirmed several deaths and injuries from the protest suppression.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Mahrang Baloch claimed that the protests were fuelled by the arrests of the BYC leader Bebarg Baloch and several members of his extended family and that three people were killed in the protests while thirteen others were injured.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Balochistan government's spokesman argued that protesters pelted police with stones, injuring ten of them in the process.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BYC continued to call for strikes for the next day.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Mahrang Baloch condemned the protest suppression on X, stating that police indiscriminately fired on the peaceful protesters.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] She along with associate members of the BYC were arrested while the former was participating at a sit-in to protest against humans rights abuses against the Baloch community.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The BYC shared a post from Mahrang Baloch that called for Balochistan's state shutdown in response to police violence.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] It posted photos and videos of various towns and cities from Balochistan participating in the shutdown by closing shops and roads and protests where participants reportedly burned tires to block the roads.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] Mobiles services were reported to have also been shut down.
[src:balochi-language/2025-jaffar-express-hijacking] The Organisation of Islamic Cooperation (OIC) also condemned the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] These attacks occurred as part of an ongoing insurgency in the Balochistan region, in which nationalist and separatist groups are seeking greater autonomy or independence from Pakistan and Iran.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Pakistani security forces responded with large-scale counter-operations across the province, stating that the operations resulted in the deaths of at least 216 militants and 22 security personnel.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Around 36 civilians were also killed in the attacks carried out by militants associated with the BLA.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The attacks were widely condemned by China, France, Turkey, the U.S.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Embassy, and the United Nations Security Council.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The attacks were also described as among the deadliest incidents in Balochistan in recent years.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Balochistan has been the site of a protracted insurgency since the late 1940s, with Baloch groups accusing the Pakistani government of exploiting the province's natural resources while marginalising local populations.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The Balochistan Liberation Army (BLA), designated as a terrorist organisation by Pakistan, the United States, and the European Union (EU), has conducted numerous attacks on security forces and infrastructure projects — including those linked to the China–Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC).
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Prior to the attacks, the insurgency had escalated since late 2019.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Before the attacks, from 25 to 29 January 2026, Pakistani intelligence-based operations in Panjgur and Harnai had killed 41 militants and insurgents of the Balochistan Liberation Army (BLA) and Pakistani Taliban (TTP) respectively.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the *Pakistan Institute for Peace Studies*, the province of Balochistan saw at least 254 terrorist attacks in 2025, which was 26% higher than the previous year, resulting in more than 400 deaths.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the provincial Chief Minister of Balochistan, Sarfraz Bugti (via a post on X), at least 700 insurgents were killed by security forces during counterinsurgency and counter-terrorism operations in the province of Balochistan in the year 2025 alone.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The militant attacks of 30 January 2026, began around 03:00 PKT and spanned at least nine districts, including Quetta, Gwadar, Mastung, Nushki, Pasni, and Kharan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Pakistani security officials, the attacks instead began at 04:00 am on Saturday with suicide blasts in Nushki and Pasni.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Witnesses stated that the attacked started around 5 AM local time.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to provincial Health Minister, Bakht Muhammad Kakar, most of the attacks had begun almost simultaneously across Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] At least a dozen towns and cities in Balochistan reported attacks being carried out.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the attacks, BLA militants and insurgents stormed banks, schools, markets, and security installations across Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The attacks were described as one of the largest and most wide-scale attacks ever done by the BLA.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Militants used guns, grenades, and suicide vests to target police stations, paramilitary outposts, a high-security prison in Quetta, and civilian vehicles.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] American-made weapons were also reportedly used by militants.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Quetta, militants stormed multiple police facilities, leading to prolonged gun battles.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to eyewitnesses, militants and insurgents riding on motorcycles were armed with grenades and assault rifles during the attacks.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to local authorities, armed men had briefly blocked roads in some parts of Quetta, and an explosion was heard near a high-security area.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Suicide bombings were reported in Mastung, Gwadar, Kharan, and Nushki.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Gwadar and Kharan, civilians were among those killed during the clashes.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Mastung, Kalat, and Pasni, militants attempted to strike government buildings and security installations.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Mastung, Kalat and Pasni, government buildings and security installations were targeted by militants and insurgents.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Pakistani security forces engaged in a three-day battle to retake Nushki — a town of about 50,000 inhabitants — from BLA forces, with local police stating that Pakistani personnel employed drones and helicopters to recover the town.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the attacks, Baloch militants targeted civilians, a prison, police stations, and paramilitary bases throughout Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The BLA seized six administrative offices during the battle of Nushki.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Insurgents targeted multiple buildings and installations belonging to both the provincial and federal governments in Nushki, including the police lines/station, a judicial complex, the deputy commissioner’s office, and a camp of the Federal Constabulary.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to police officials, the insurgents were at one point within 1 km (3,300 ft) of the provincial chief minister's office in Quetta before being repelled.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Multiple buildings were also set ablaze during battle of Nushki.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In the Nushki district, militants attempted to storm the provincial headquarters of the Frontier Corps, but the attack was repelled, according to the Balochistan Police.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Balochistan Constabulary, the desert town of Nushki was secured by local law enforcement after a three-day battle during which 7 police officers were killed.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to security officials, helicopters and drones were used against militants in the city of Nushki to help drive out BLA-affiliated militants and insurgents.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] By 1 February, Pakistani officials reported that security forces had thwarted most attempts, engaging in clearance operations that lasted into the following day and went on till 5 February.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to officials, the Baloch Liberation Army (BLA) made announcements through mosques ahead of the attacks, asking people to join and support them, claiming to be waging a war to take over all government buildings and installations in the province.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Pakistani security forces, foreign handlers of the Baloch militants and insurgents, including their operatives, were present at the sites of the attacks and helped to coordinate them.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Pakistani security officials and the Pakistan Army, multiple attacks were attempted and carried out in Quetta, Nushki, Dalbandin, Kalat, Gwadar, Pasni, Tump, and Mastung, stating that clearance operations were continuing in areas affected by the attacks.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Shahid Rind, most of the attacks by the BLA were foiled.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The Baloch Liberation Army later subsequently released the Nushki Deputy Commissioner, Muhammad Hussain Hazara and Assistant commissioner, Maria Shamaoon, who had been taken hostage earlier.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Nushki Assistant Commissioner, Maria Shamoon, "On January 31, at around 5:30 in the morning, some miscreants snuck into our homes and took over the property".
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] She also added that the militants took over the government complex and had taken the deputy commissioner, Hussain Hazara, hostage as well.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Additional troops were deployed to Nushki, after a three-day-long battle with militants to recapture the town, in order to reinforce it, according to security officials.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the subsequent shootout and standoff between the MSA and PCG on one side and the pinned-down insurgents on the other, all 5 of the remaining militants were killed.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] 1 MSA soldier was killed, and another was injured over the course of the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In total, 7 BLA insurgents/militants were killed in and around the town of Pasni.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Balochistan police, militants also tried to abduct passengers in Pasni who were travelling on buses along highways.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Out of all cities and towns in Balochistan, the provincial capital of Quetta emerged as by far the most targeted and affected by them.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Quetta's red zone, police personnel including a deputy superintendent were killed.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] On Quetta’s Saryab Road, armed gunmen opened fire on a moving police van.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The policemen retaliated with gunfire, and paramilitary Frontier Corpsmen also joined the gunfight later on.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] 4 of the attacking insurgents were killed during the exchange of gunshots, and the area was soon secured by security forces.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Provincial Health Minister Of Balochistan, Bakht Muhammad Kakar, 2 police officers were killed in a grenade attack on a police vehicle in Quetta.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to witnesses in Quetta, 3 police stations set on fire by the attackers, who wreaked havoc throughout the city before security forces arrived on the scene to stop them and a military helicopter was seen firing shells at the insurgents and militants.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A bank was set ablaze and several police vehicles were torched, which caused widespread panic among the local populace.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Kharan, Shahid Malazai, a tribal and political leader, along with 6 of his bodyguards, were killed when gunmen stormed Malazai's residence.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The 3 insurgents who were responsible for Malazai's killing were killed during another exchange of fire in Kharan later on.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A labourers’ colony in Gwadar was also attacked by insurgents, resulting in the deaths of 5 members of a labour family who were from Khuzdar.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Militants attacked a camp in which migrant workers were residing, killing 11 people, according to Atta-ur-Rehman, a senior police officer in Gwadar.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Those killed included 5 men, 3 women and 3 children.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Balochistan Constabulary, militants also tried to abduct passengers in Gwadar who were travelling along highways on buses.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Mastung, gunfire and explosions injured several people, including a police officer, while an attack on a prison in Mastung was repelled.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] It was, however, after at least 30 prisoners had already escaped from it.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Kalat, clashes reportedly took place near the District Collector headquarters and police stations.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Also in Kalat, attacks by militants and insurgents on police stations and banks injured 3 policemen and forced local shops to shut due to fear and uncertainty over the situation.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Nasirabad, security forces defused explosive material planted on a railway track.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In Khuzdar, residents claimed to have witnessed BLA militants capturing 7 members of the security forces.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Later in February, the group released footage claiming to have captured 7 Pakistani soldiers with a footage.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The Baloch Liberation Front claimed to have participated in the attacks alongside the Baloch Liberation Army.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Pakistani security forces, foreign handlers of the Baloch militants and insurgents, including their operatives, were in direct communication with them during the attacks, with some being present at the sites of the attacks and where they had helped to coordinate them.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In response to the attacks, Pakistan's Defence Minister, Khawaja Asif, urged a surge in the deployment of troops to Balochistan in order to combat the attacks and deteriorating security situation.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The operation had ended by 5 February and had resulted in the deaths of 216 militants and insurgents, according to the Armed Forces' media wing, the ISPR.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the operation, security forces had launched fresh raids in the districts of Panjgur and Harnai targeting hideouts/camps of the BLA in Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the ISPR, because of the coordinated engagements and clearance operations, 216 militants were killed, and the BLA's leadership, command-and-control structures, and operational capabilities were significantly weakened as a result.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Operations began on January 29 in Panjgur and the outskirts of Harnai district after an imminent threat was indicated by verified intelligence.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] In this initial phase, 41 militants linked to local insurgent networks were eliminated.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Subsequent responses by security forces had thwarted further attacks by BLA, followed by expanded intelligence-based operations across multiple areas to dismantle sleeper cells through sustained clearance and sanitisation operations.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the operation, a large cache of foreign-origin weapons, ammunition, explosives, and equipment was recovered, with preliminary analysis indicating systematic external facilitation and logistical support.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The military stated that it was committed to counter terrorism under the National Action Plan (NAP) and vowed that operations would continue until all threats are eliminated.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] ISPR described the operation as reflecting Balochistan’s preference (and of Pakistan’s as a whole) for peace, unity, and development over violence.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to the Inter-Services Public Relations, Operation Radd-ul-Fitna-1 had concluded by 5 February, after a several-day-long, intelligence-driven campaign launched in response to BLA's wave of attacks across Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Shahid Rind, the official spokesperson of Balochistan chief minister, Sarfaraz Bugti, illegal small arms, recoilless rifles, anti-aircraft guns and rocket-propelled grenade launchers were also found in some homes during the operations.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] He also stated that at least 100 suspects believed to have been involved in the attacks were arrested by security forces.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A group of about 25 militants and criminals, led by a man by the name of Mirak Khan Chakrani, had surrendered to local authorities after the conclusion of operation Radd ul Fitna-1, during which they also handed over a large quantity of weapons and ammunition to authorities.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The group had been involved in militancy, looting, as well as robbery and extortion.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The group had surrendered after efforts by security forces and Mir Aftab Bugti, the brother of Balochistan's Chief Minister.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Mirak Khan Chakrani also announced his joining of the Chakrani Peace Force in order to support efforts against extremist elements.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Section 144 was imposed across Balochistan for one month, citing the overall "law-and-order situation".
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Authorities banned vehicles with tinted windows and prohibited gatherings of 5 or more people, including political or religious processions, without approval from the relevant district administration.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A notification warned that violators would face legal action under Section 188, including imprisonment of up to 6 months.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Due to the attacks and fragile security situation, mobile data services were suspended for some time in Quetta and internet services in general were temporarily shut in other parts of Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The Balochistan health department declared an emergency at all government hospitals across the province to treat those injured in the attacks.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Balochistan’s health minister, Bakht Muhammad Kakar, instructed health officials and hospitals to ensure immediate medical care for those injured.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Health facilities in Quetta were placed on high alert, and additional doctors were deployed in order to treat the victims of the attacks.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Shahid Rind, a spokesman of Balochistan's provincial government, most of the attacks by the Baloch Liberation Army had been repelled or foiled.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Shahid Rind, the official spokesperson of Balochistan chief minister, Sarfaraz Bugti, by 5 February, most areas in Balochistan where attacks had occurred had been cleared, except for Quetta, where search and combing operations were still ongoing.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] He said to reporters during a press conference in Quetta that "The situation across the province is normal, including in Nushki and Quetta".
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] He also stated that at least 100 suspects, who were arrested during the combing and search operations in Quetta, were also being investigated.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] He further stated that "The identification of terrorists killed in the operations is ongoing".
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Shahid Rind also said that the exams of 8th and 9th-grade students in Quetta will continue as usual, adding that the polio vaccination campaign will also resume its operations in Balochistan, except for Nushki.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Rind stated all highways in Balochistan were open for vehicles, except for a small part of a road in Nushki, which was damaged by explosions during the battle for the town.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] He added that local authorities are busy repairing the road, and it will become open for traffic after a period of 12 to 24 hours.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Internet and mobile data services had continued to be non-operational by early morning of 5 February, despite rail services having been restored.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the attacks, Pakistan Railways suspended train services from Balochistan to all other parts of the country for 4 days, but restored service by 5 February later in the day, after counter-operations by security forces had concluded.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Initial reports varied, but by 5 February, official figures confirmed 22 security personnel (including law enforcement and paramilitary forces) as well as 36 civilians killed (including women, children, elders, and labourers), with an unspecified number injured.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] During the counter-operations, 216 militants were killed, bringing the total death toll to 274.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The BLA claimed to have killed 280 security personnel and taken 18 security personnel prisoner.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] However, the BLA provided no proof to back their claims.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] It also initially claimed that 18 of its fighters were killed.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] It later admitted to losing at least 92 of its fighters during the attacks by 6 February.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] According to Pakistani authorities, at least 133 insurgents and militants had been killed across Balochistan over the course of 2 days from 31 January to 1 February, with 92 militants/insurgents killed on 31 January alone (with 16 security personnel and 31 civilians having also been killed).
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A total of 216 militants/insurgents were reportedly killed overall from 29 January to 2 February.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Analysts described it as the single deadliest day for Balochi insurgents in decades, due to the sheer amount of militants/insurgents killed in such a short duration of time.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Pakistani officials condemned the attacks as attempts to undermine stability in Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] International statements included condemnation of the incident and solidarity with Pakistan from China, Turkey, Qatar, France, and the United States.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] Members of the United Nations Security Council described the attacks as heinous and cowardly, and condemned them in the strongest terms.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] The UNSC also held BLA responsible for the attacks on civilians and expressed sympathy with the victims of the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-balochistan-attacks] A total of 48 Pakistani nationals were killed in the attacks, which included 17 security personnel and 31 civilians, according to the UNSC.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] On 24 May 2026, a vehicle-borne suicide bombing targeted a shuttle train near Chaman Phatak in Quetta, Balochistan, Pakistan.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The explosion killed at least 47 people and injured 98 others.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The train was carrying Pakistani security personnel and their family members from Quetta's cantonment area to connect with the *Jaffar Express*.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The Balochistan Liberation Army claimed responsibility for the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Quetta is the capital of Balochistan, a province affected by a long-running separatist insurgency.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Militants in the province have targeted security forces, government installations, civilians and infrastructure.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Before the 2026 bombing, there had been several high-profile incidents involving railway and security targets in Balochistan, including the 2024 Quetta railway station bombing and the 2025 *Jaffar Express* hijacking.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The BLA has claimed that the Pakistani government profits from Balochistan's mineral resources without sufficient benefit to local communities.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] A day before the attack, nine suspected militants and four officials from the Counter Terrorism Department were killed in a shootout on the outskirts of Quetta.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] PKT, an explosives-laden vehicle struck one of the carriages of a shuttle train near Chaman Phatak as the train was travelling through Quetta.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Railway authorities said the train was travelling from Quetta Cantonment towards the city's railway station, where passengers were to connect with the *Jaffar Express*.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Reuters, citing Pakistan's railways ministry, reported that the blast derailed the engine and three coaches, and that two coaches overturned.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The explosion occurred in a residential area and damaged nearby buildings and vehicles.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Images and videos from the scene showed burned vehicles, damaged buildings, smoke and train carriages on their sides.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Police, the Counter-Terrorism Department, bomb disposal personnel, security forces and rescue workers responded to the site.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Pakistan Railways dispatched rescue trucks and a relief train.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Rescue officials said 47 people were killed, including 20 soldiers, and 98 others were injured.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Officials said security personnel, passengers, bystanders and residents of nearby houses were among the casualties.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The Balochistan government said three Frontier Corps personnel and a family of four were among those killed.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Women and children were also reported among the injured.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] A medical emergency was declared in public hospitals in Quetta, and doctors, paramedics and other staff were ordered to remain on duty.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] According to the Associated Press, doctors said 20 of the injured were in critical condition.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The Balochistan Liberation Army (BLA) claimed responsibility for the attack and said it had targeted security personnel on the train.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Reuters reported that it could not independently verify the group's casualty claim.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The BLA identified the alleged bomber as 25-year-old Bilal Shahwani, a resident of Killi Sarde, and said he was a member of the Majeed Brigade.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Pakistani security forces reportedly raided Shahwani's home and detained several of his relatives.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Security forces cordoned off the area after the explosion, and the district administration established a control room at the office of the Quetta deputy commissioner.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The provincial Home Department also activated a monitoring and coordination cell.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif, President Asif Ali Zardari, Balochistan chief minister Sarfraz Bugti, railways minister Hanif Abbasi and Deputy Prime Minister Ishaq Dar condemned the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The Human Rights Commission of Pakistan said it was alarmed by the security situation in Balochistan and by attacks on civilians, workers, passengers, law enforcement personnel and public infrastructure.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] China, Qatar and Saudi Arabia condemned the attack.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] António Guterres, the secretary-general of the United Nations, condemned the attack and wished a swift recovery to those affected.
[src:balochi-language/2026-quetta-train-bombing] The Afghan Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the United States Embassy in Islamabad, the Chinese Embassy in Islamabad and Global Affairs Canada also condemned the attack.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi varieties constitute a dialect continuum and collectively at least have 10 million native speakers.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The main varieties of Balochi are Eastern (*Soleimani*), Southern (*Makrani*) and Western (*Rakhshani*).
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Koroshi is a dialect of the Balochi language, spoken mainly in the provinces of Fars and Hormozgan of Iran.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] However, Josef Elfenbein of *Encyclopædia Iranica* divides the dialects of the Balochi language into six categories: Rakhshani, Panjguri, Saravani, Lashari, Kechi, and the "Coastal Dialects".
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi belongs to the Western Iranian subgroup, and its original homeland is suggested to be around the central Caspian region.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi uses the letter *Waw* with a diacritic in its spelling (ۏ).
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi is an Indo-European language, spoken by the Baloch and belonging to the Indo-Iranian branch of the family.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] As an Iranian language, it is classified within the Northwestern Iranian group.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] According to the research of Swedish academic Carina Jahani, ISO 639-3 groups Southern, Eastern, and Western Baloch under the Balochi macrolanguage, keeping Koroshi separate.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The Balochi vowel system has at least eight vowels: five long and three short.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The short vowels have more centralized phonetic quality than the long vowels.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The variety spoken in Karachi also has nasalized vowels, most importantly /ẽː/ and /ãː/.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In addition to these eight vowels, Balochi has two vowel glides, that is /aw/ and /aj/.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The following table shows consonants which are common to both Western (Northern) and Southern Balochi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The consonants /s/, /z/, /n/, /ɾ/ and /l/ are articulated as alveolar in Western Balochi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The plosives /t/ and /d/ are dental in both dialects.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The symbol ń is used to denote nasalization of the preceding vowel.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In Eastern Balochi, it is noted that the stop and glide consonants may also occur as aspirated allophones in word initial position as [pʰ tʰ ʈʰ t͡ʃʰ kʰ] and [wʱ].
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Allophones of stops in postvocalic position include for voiceless stops, [f θ x] and for voiced stops [β ð ɣ]. /n l/ are also dentalized as [n̪ l̪].
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Difference between a question and a statement is marked with the tone, when there is no question word.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Rising tone marks the question and falling tone the statement.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Statements and questions with a question word are characterized by falling intonation at the end of the sentence.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Questions without a question word are characterized by rising intonation at the end of the sentence.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Both coordinate and subordinate clauses that precede the final clause in the sentence have rising intonation.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The final clause in the sentence has falling intonation.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The normal word order is subject–object–verb.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Similar to many other Indo-Iranian languages, Balochi also features split ergativity.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The subject is marked as nominative except for the past tense constructions where the subject of a transitive verb is marked as oblique and the verb agrees with the object.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi, similar to many Western Iranian languages, has lost the Old Iranian gender distinctions.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Much of the Balochi number system is identical to Persian.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The Makrani dialect is spoken in the southern parts of Balochistan (notably Makran), including coastal areas such as Gwadar, Pasni, Turbat, and Karachi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The dialect (despite the higher prevalence of the Rakshani) is also spoken in some coastal areas of the Sistan-Baluchestan province in cities such as: Qasr-e Qand, Nik Shahr, Rask, Chabahar, and Bandar Abbas.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] There are two main sub-dialects: the dialect of the *Mandwani* (northern) tribes and the dialect of the *Domki* (southern) tribes.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The dialectal differences are not very significant.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] One difference is that grammatical terminations in the northern dialect are less distinct compared with those in the southern tribes.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The Soleimani dialect is spoken mainly in eastern Balochistan, western Punjab, and parts of Sindh—all within Pakistan—particularly in areas such as Quetta, Kalat, Khuzdar, Lasbela, Chagai, Noshki, Dalbandin, Kharan, Mastung, the Kacchi Plains, Dera Ghazi Khan, Taunsa, Rajanpur, and Jacobabad.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] While the Makrani and Rakshani dialects are close, the Soleimani dialect is often perceived as farther from the other two in terms of intelligibility.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] This is likely due to influence from languages such as Brahvi, Pashto, Sindhi, and Punjabi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The Rakshani dialect is predominantly spoken in western Balochistan, including parts of Iran and Afghanistan.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Commonly spoken in the Sistan-Baluchestan province and Khorasan region within Iran.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] An isolated dialect is Koroshi, which is spoken in the Qashqai tribal confederation in the Fars province.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Koroshi distinguishes itself in grammar and lexicon among Balochi varieties.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Balochi was not a written language before the 19th century, and the Persian script was used to write Balochi wherever necessary.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] However, Balochi was still spoken at Baloch courts.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] British colonial officers first wrote Balochi with the Latin script.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Following the creation of Pakistan, Baloch scholars adopted the Persian alphabet.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The first collection of poetry in Balochi, *Gulbang* by Mir Gul Khan Nasir, was published in 1951 and incorporated the Arabic script.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] It was much later that Syed Zahoor Shah Hashemi wrote a comprehensive guidance on the usage of Arabic script and standardized it as the Balochi orthography in Pakistan and Iran.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] This earned him the title of the "father of Balochi".
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] His guidelines are widely used in eastern and western Balochistan.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In Afghanistan, Balochi is still written in a modified Arabic script based on Persian.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In 2002, a conference in Quetta was held to help standardize the script that would be used for Balochi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The following alphabet was used by Syed Zahoor Shah Hashmi in his lexicon of Balochi *Syed ay Ganj* (سید اے گنج; lit.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Until the creation of the Balochi Standard Alphabet, it was by far the most widely used alphabet for writing Balochi, and is still used very frequently.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The Balochi Standard Alphabet, standardized by the Balochi Academy Sarbaz, consists of 29 letters.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] It is an extension of the Perso-Arabic script and borrows a few glyphs from Urdu.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] It is also sometimes referred to as *Balo-Rabi* or *Balòrabi*.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Today, it is the preferred script to use in a professional setting and by the educated.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The following Latin-based alphabet was adopted by the International Workshop on "Balochi Roman Orthography" (University of Uppsala, Sweden, 28–30 May 2000).
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The alphabet was used for several texts, including children's books, newspapers, and ideological works.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In 1938, however, the official use of Balochi was discontinued.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In 1989, Mammad Sherdil, a teacher from the Turkmen SSR, approached Balochi language researcher Sergei Axenov with the idea of creating a Cyrillic-based alphabet for Balochi.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] Before this, the Cyrillic script was already used for writing Balochi and was used in several publications but the alphabet was not standardized.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] The project was approved with some minor changes (қ, *ꝑ*, and ы were removed due to the rarity of these sounds in Balochi, and о̄ was added).
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] From 1992 to 1993, several primary school textbooks were printed in this script.
[src:balochi-language/balochi-language] In the early 2000s, the script fell out of use.
